SIMPLE: transport
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Transport
<hw>Trans*port"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Transported</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Transporting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>transporter</ets>,
L. <ets>transportare</ets>; <ets>trans</ets> across + <ets>portare</ets>
to carry. See <er>Port</er> bearing, demeanor.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To carry or bear from one place to another; to remove; to convey;
<as>as, to <ex>transport</ex> goods; to <ex>transport</ex>
troops.</as></def> <rj><au>Hakluyt.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To carry, or cause to be carried, into banishment,
as a criminal; to banish.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To carry away with vehement emotion, as joy, sorrow,
complacency, anger, etc.; to ravish with pleasure or ecstasy; <as>as,
music <ex>transports</ex> the soul</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[They] laugh as if <qex>transported</qex> with some fit⟦br⟧
Of passion.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We shall then be <qex>transported</qex> with a nobler . . .
wonder.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Transport</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Transport
<hw>Trans"port</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. See
<er>Transport</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Transportation; carriage; conveyance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Romans . . . stipulated with the Carthaginians to furnish them
with ships for <qex>transport</qex> and war.</q>
<rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A vessel employed for transporting, especially for
carrying soldiers, warlike stores, or provisions, from one place to
another, or to convey convicts to their destination; -- called also
<altname>transport ship</altname>, <altname>transport
vessel</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Vehement emotion; passion; ecstasy;
rapture.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With <qex>transport</qex> views the airy rule his own,⟦br⟧
And swells on an imaginary throne.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Say not, in <qex>transports</qex> of despair,⟦br⟧
That all your hopes are fled.</q> <rj><qau>Doddridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A convict transported, or sentenced to
exile.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Transportability</ent>⟦br⟧
